# Changing Attributes üè∑Ô∏è

You can change the value of an attribute (like `src` or `href`).

```javascript
document.getElementById("myImage").src = "landscape.jpg";

// Or using setAttribute
const link = document.querySelector("a");
link.setAttribute("href", "https://google.com");
```

# Class List üè´

A cleaner way to change styles is to add/remove CSS classes.

```javascript
const element = document.getElementById("myDiv");

// Add a class
element.classList.add("active");

// Remove a class
element.classList.remove("hidden");

// Toggle a class (add if missing, remove if present)
element.classList.toggle("dark-mode");
```

# Creating Nodes üèóÔ∏è

To add a new element to the HTML DOM, you must create the element (element node) first, and then append it to an existing element.

```javascript
const para = document.createElement("p");
const node = document.createTextNode("This is new.");
para.appendChild(node);

const element = document.getElementById("div1");
element.appendChild(para);
```

# Removing Elements üóëÔ∏è

To remove an HTML element, you use `.remove()` on the element itself.

```javascript
const elm = document.getElementById("p1");
elm.remove();
```

Older way (remove child from parent):
```javascript
const parent = document.getElementById("div1");
const child = document.getElementById("p1");
parent.removeChild(child);
```

